<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-441-177  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 441 177.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Sept 24 1990 v7 n38 p151(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Long-term planning, achievable goals key to avoiding crisismanagement. (US Commerce Department survey indicates that crisismanagement is 'epidemic')</TITLE><AUTHOR>Eskow, Dennis.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>A study by the US Department of Commerce indicates that crisismanagement is 'epidemic' among American corporations and thatmanagers must learn more effective decision making methods toavoid its ill effects.andP;  Many people prefer crisis managementbecause the risk is low and it involves little accountabilitybecause they can say that 'the project was going to fail anyway.'andO;Experts suggest that managers give themselves 30 minutes ofuninterrupted 'think time' daily and develop goals before making adecision.andP;  Managers should also review corporate history todetermine how they can avoid predecessors' mistakes.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Crisis managementManagement of EDPDecision MakingReportsUnited States. Department of CommerceStrategic PlanningGoals and Objectives.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Long-Term Planning, Achievable Goals Key to Avoiding Crisis ManagementandM;Crisis management is epidemic in corporate America and will continue tospread its ill effects until managers learn to make decisions moreeffectively, a leading management consultant says.andP;  A recent U.S.andP;  CommerceDepartment survey backs up the contention, noting that managers make mostdecisions on the run because they spend nearly half of their time inmeetings.andM;&quot;It all stems from a ready-fire aim approach to decision making,&quot; said GordonMiller, president of Decision Training Systems, of Keene, N.H.andP;  He spoke atthe annual meeting of the microcomputer industry's Association of BetterComputer Dealers (ABCD) in New Orleans earlier this month.andM;&quot;Let's face it,&quot; he said.andP;  &quot;People prefer crisis management.andP;  It's easier.andO;There's little accountability and very low risk.andP;  After all, the project wasgoing to fail anyway.andP;  How we decide on technology can be loaded withquestions that put things off until there's a crisis and a decision has to bemade.&quot;andM;In addition, Miller said, decision makers frequently hide behind the factthat they're too busy to plan.andM;The Commerce Department study, conducted at 60 large corporations in June,found that managers spend an average of 18 hours per week in meetings, abouthalf the work week at the corporations studied.andM;&quot;Usually, there's follow-up and preparation time for the meetings,&quot; saidMichael Kassner, the Commerce Department analyst who led the study.andP;  &quot;It's athorny issue.andP;  Managers too often let themselves get mired in busyness sothat they can't get down to business.&quot;andM;To overcome busyness, Miller suggested that managers give themselves 30minutes of &quot;think time&quot; every day.andP;  &quot;This is dedicated time with notelephone, no talk, no messaging--just thinking,&quot; he said.andP;  In addition,managers have to target their efforts; they have to ask themselves what theirobjective is.andM;&quot;When things get out of hand for me, I can almost always trace it back to nothaving a goal,&quot; acknowledged Walter Myra, director of information technologyat Rainbow Pharmacies in Beltsville, Md.andP;  &quot;A lot of times you believe youhave a goal, but when you analyze it, the language and the thinking are toovague.andP;  'Increase profits' isn't a goal, it's business.andP;  'Increaseproductivity' isn't really a goal, either--not unless there are precisemeasurements and benchmarks.&quot;andM;Developing a goal means having a plan with a simply stated target, Millersaid, adding that most managers can develop clearer targets by establishing aset of values or standards for success.andM;&quot;By placing emphasis on productivity, the manager may see crises onlyrarely,&quot; he said.andM;Managers need to review corporate history before entering into creativeprocesses, according to Myra.andM;&quot;We have to go back in time and ask not how did we do that before, since thatcould be wrong, but ask what were the main activities of the past year ortwo,&quot; he said.andP;  &quot;By making a list of the highlights, by focusing on the bigevents in corporate history, you can get a handle on what the company reallystands for.andM;&quot;It's never as obvious as you think.&quot;andO;</TEXT></DOC>